{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"57e5281c-d00d-4ba1-af8f-e286e8324817","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). They contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread state.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (full memory dump), macOS uses `/cores/core.<pid>`, but core dumps are disabled by default. Enable with:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file will appear in `/cores/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4d2956be-2674-4ed1-99ab-0c4ddebbc44f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no code changes needed.","outputTokens":267},"id":"28f97d41-bdd0-4464-adc8-fc88239f98da","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:54:33.811Z","parentId":"10166de2-b3bc-4469-9c91-e3adbc6d29a9"}
